AB  - In this study of attitudes among industrial workers at a plant in the US, the analysis reveals differences between white males on one side, and women and minorities on the other side. Specifically, the survey question targeted was in order to succeed, the union should work with outside groups such as civil rights and environmental groups. In efforts to ascertain this information, data was collected on a survey that was administered to a major industrial union of 1,020 workers in 2007. The results follow similar findings in other studies that white males specifically, and whites in general in the working class are diverging in social attitudes compared to their minority and female coworkers. Generally, women and minorities are consistently liberal, while white males in particular are consistently conservative. This has significant ramifications for organized labor, labor politics and wider gender relations.
